<div id="review_2443930407" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2443930407" />
    <a title="Tobias" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/83780111-tobias"><img alt="Tobias" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1641664499p2/83780111.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2443930407?book_show_action=true">May 04, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tobias" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tobias" href="/user/show/83780111-tobias">Tobias</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2443930407" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9079916394950488358">A nice short introduction to anarchist thought by Noam Chomsky. Some prior knowledge of anarchism and other ideologies seems to be presupposed, though. The first part of the book struck me as a little incoherent and didn&apos;t feel like a great way to open. The part about objectivity and liberal scholarship was a nice surprise; where the author looked at the Spanish revolution of 1936 and its portrayal by scholars. Chomsky writes rather accessibly and states his arguments clearly. Decent little book</span>
  <span id="freeText9079916394950488358" style="display:none">A nice short introduction to anarchist thought by Noam Chomsky. Some prior knowledge of anarchism and other ideologies seems to be presupposed, though. The first part of the book struck me as a little incoherent and didn't feel like a great way to open. The part about objectivity and liberal scholarship was a nice surprise; where the author looked at the Spanish revolution of 1936 and its portrayal by scholars. Chomsky writes rather accessibly and states his arguments clearly. Decent little book.</span>
