    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3651662549" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3651662549" />
    <a title="Anderson R" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/86452254-anderson-r"><img alt="Anderson R" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3651662549?book_show_action=true">Nov 20, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anderson R" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anderson R" href="/user/show/86452254-anderson-r">Anderson R</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3651662549" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8634107961979880999">In this collection of essays introduced by Nathan Schneider, Noam Chomsky approaches the topic of Anarchism. Chomsky presents Anarchism as a broad and complicated set of beliefs that seem to phase in and out of popularity over the years. These beliefs are usually left-wing, as the author of some of the first anarchist literature was a classical libertarian. They boast a strong belief in individual rights outside of any economic system. He also approaches many of the fallacies and concerns surrou</span>
  <span id="freeText8634107961979880999" style="display:none">In this collection of essays introduced by Nathan Schneider, Noam Chomsky approaches the topic of Anarchism. Chomsky presents Anarchism as a broad and complicated set of beliefs that seem to phase in and out of popularity over the years. These beliefs are usually left-wing, as the author of some of the first anarchist literature was a classical libertarian. They boast a strong belief in individual rights outside of any economic system. He also approaches many of the fallacies and concerns surrounding this subject, discussing things such as bureaucracy and democracy and how they would fit into an anarchist society. Out of all the essays contained in this book, I found the one titles "Language and Freedom" to be the most interesting. I found the analyses of language and the mind provided by excerpts from the writings of philosophers such as Descartes and Rousseau fascinating. I also liked the way Chomsky eventually tied these writings in with anarchist thought and the commodification of human life. Overall, I believe this book clarified many questions I previously had concerning anarchist thought and it also opened my eyes to things that I had not thought about prior, such as the way leftists aesthetics were often co-opted into mainstream trends and then completely abandoned. While it didn't have any glaring faults, it also wasn't mindblowing so I give it 4/5 stars.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8634107961979880999" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


