    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_185088853" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/185088853" />
    <a title="Papsotherboy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5803209-papsotherboy"><img alt="Papsotherboy" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/185088853?book_show_action=true">Jul 14, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Papsotherboy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Papsotherboy" href="/user/show/5803209-papsotherboy">Papsotherboy</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9781849350372" href="/book/show/8863165-chomsky-on-anarchism">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer185088853" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1222372987855875606">This book is not about anarchism, but about Chomskyism. Throughout the entire book, Chomsky never bothers to define what he means by &quot;anarchy,&quot; and doesn&apos;t bother to inform the reader of what he thinks anarchy is. He refers to &quot;human nature&quot; instead of repeatedly saying &quot;you know?&quot; as a mechanism of conveniently avoiding explanation.<br/><br/>From Chomsky&apos;s point of view, anarchy seems to conform most closely with anarcho-syndicalism, which is nothing more than a decentralized form of democracy that conce</span>
  <span id="freeText1222372987855875606" style="display:none">This book is not about anarchism, but about Chomskyism. Throughout the entire book, Chomsky never bothers to define what he means by "anarchy," and doesn't bother to inform the reader of what he thinks anarchy is. He refers to "human nature" instead of repeatedly saying "you know?" as a mechanism of conveniently avoiding explanation.<br /><br />From Chomsky's point of view, anarchy seems to conform most closely with anarcho-syndicalism, which is nothing more than a decentralized form of democracy that concentrates power in the hands of a few union bosses.<br /><br />His failure to credit other researchers for their seminal works is criminally unacademic. He ignores the accomplishments of entire academic disciplines and attempts to garner credit for their efforts by modifying the terms he uses to describe classes of phenomena. Thus, others become Chomskyized by this type of piracy.<br /><br />His research into the attributes, origins, and legitimacy of the state is grossly incompetent, leading him to erroneous conclusions. His work is filled with biases that stem from his Yiddish/American urban background. He has cultivated an elitist status that was achieved by associating himself with high profile and controversial institutions and figures, notably MIT and B.F. Skinner.<br /><br />Chomsky has spent most of his career reinventing himself, but maintains that he is a "linguist." All of his linguistic efforts center around STRUCTURAL linguistics, completely ignoring historical linguistics and cognitive science. Chomsky can approach some topics with rationality, common sense and the aplomb of a great vocabulary. This is especially so in the case of state supported terrorism, which should be crystal clear to everyone, if not for the efforts of authoritarian autocrats. His research into the source of authority and state authoritarianism reflects a head-in-the-sand attitude that almost any historically apprised person would find unfathomable.<br /><br />Much of the interviews and other materials included in this book have absolutely no relevance to the title and topic presented on the cover. Some of the material rambles so pointlessly that it is obvious that Mr. Chomsky was paid according to the word count, or compensated gratuitously for merely showing up for an interview.<br /><br />Mr. Chomsky has a bush growing in his yard that he must manicure with a rug beater. Grass doesn't grow around this bush. The first 150 or so pages of this book are a complete waste of of paper and ink, dated, and skewed beyond relevance. The following 75 or so pages of the book more-or-less adequately describe the state and the relationships of people and persons to the state and state-like institutions.<br /><br />Any serious scholar with an interest in such topics would be far better served by studying a course in social anthropology than by reading anything that the prevaricating Mr. Chomsky has to say.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1222372987855875606" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


